00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:09.720
I'm 51 now, so I'll be 76 then.

72
00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:14.109
But at that time, there'll be double the number of people over 65 as there are

73
00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:18.000
today. By the time I'm 85, so in 2060,

74
00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:21.960
thereabout, there'll be about three or four times as many people aged 85 and

75
00:04:22.101 --> 00:04:23.180
over as there are today.

76
00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:26.380
Potentially as many as four times as many.

77
00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:30.200
So you and I and all of us who are around that age will be

78
00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:34.030
looking to use infrastructure such as hospitals and

79
00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:37.080
aged care facilities, and accessible housing,

80
00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:42.060
that is currently not in existence at the levels that we need it and for

81
00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:45.480
which there's no real clear plan to build in a

82
00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:48.560
hurry. So we've got this really profound demographic shift happening.

83
00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:52.020
We don't have a strategic plan to match it, is essentially the message I wanted to

84
00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:53.380
get across to you guys today.

85
00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:57.620
The numbers on the graph are quite sobering because there's no roadmap.

86
00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:01.980
And there's going to be significant and compounding shortages, I think, in housing

87
00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:05.720
and aged care facilities and care infrastructure in particular.

88
00:05:05.780 --> 00:05:07.580
Those are the three areas that I really

89
00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:12.200
felt that there were big lacks in. And then there's this extra area, which is urban

90
00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:15.120
design, which I think is an opportunity area for us as well.

91
00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:17.640
So I'll cover those four areas.

92
00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:21.540
We've got increasing life expectancy, declining birth rates.

93
00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:25.340
We've got internal migration pressures, international migration pressures,

94
00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:28.160
and that's led to this thing of structural aging.

95
00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:30.040
If you put the next slide on, please.

96
00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:38.120
So structural aging essentially means that the population's shifting from a

97
00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:41.900
pyramid shape with lots of young people at the bottom to a pyramid more an

98
00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:45.900
obelisk shape with fewer young people at the bottom and a lot more older people

99
00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:46.400
at the top.

100
00:05:47.800 --> 00:05:51.700
It's quite hard to read, but the bottom right-hand pyramid is 2053, so about,

101
00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:56.140
what's that, 25 years away or so. You can see that top line just getting

102
00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.830
older and older. And the bottom line is slowly getting shorter.

103
00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:03.440
So there's fewer people to essentially pay for the infrastructure that the older

104
00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:07.370
people are going to need. And you'll have heard all the Treasury's concerns about

105
00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:11.250
that, I'm sure.It's a non-reversible

106
00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:14.490
trend, and we're sharing it with all OECD countries, essentially.

107
00:06:14.770 --> 00:06:15.990
Some of them are further ahead than us.

108
00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:20.510
We can slow it down with immigration, but we can't stop it, so

109
00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:21.790
it's going to keep going.

110
00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:25.570
And by the way, it's not necessarily a bad story.

111
00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:29.010
Having everyone live longer and happier and healthier lives is a great story.

112
00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:32.150
I'll be thrilled to have a long, happy life.

113
00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:35.750
But we just need to be planning for it, so it's just a systems challenge and

114
00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:37.910
opportunity, but it's not a crisis.

115
00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:41.830
But it could become one if we don't treat it as something we have to

116
00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:44.630
proactively address. Yeah.

117
00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:47.590
Next slide, please.

118
00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:51.070
So the total number of older people is really relevant in terms of the

119
00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.330
infrastructure and facilities we need, obviously, but the proportion of the older

120
00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:56.990
population is relevant in terms of how we actually pay for it.

121
00:06:57.330 --> 00:07:00.630
So currently, about 17% of the population's over 65.

122
00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:04.660
By 2078, that'll move to around 30%, or one third of the population.

123
00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:08.330
So that will mean fewer people to pay for more services

124
00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:11.950
and more infrastructure. Next slide, please.

125
00:07:12.830 --> 00:07:16.090
I'm trying to rattle through this demographic stuff because I know you probably

126
00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:17.090
know this stuff quite well.

127
00:07:18.110 --> 00:07:21.810
Regional disparities, this map on the left is now, and the

128
00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:25.890
next one is 2048, so just showing the percentage of older people in

129
00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:29.830
each area over time. Some areas like Tasman, Nelson,

130
00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:33.470
Marlborough, are already what's known as hyper-aged, so they've already got more

131
00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:37.290
than 20% of people over 65. And those areas are going to be

132
00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:41.330
growing older faster and will have around 30% of people over

133
00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:45.470
65 by 2048, within two decades. And then

134
00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:48.410
other areas like Auckland, Christchurch, Wellington, they're growing older much

135
00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:51.880
slower as a percentage. But in terms of overall numbers, they're growing older

136
00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:55.310
quite quickly. So Auckland, for example, within 20 odd years, will have an

137
00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:58.650
extra couple of hundred thousand people over 65.

138
00:07:58.690 --> 00:08:02.670
So the challenges for the big cities is more about the absolute number of

139
00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:06.570
people. I think for the smaller places, it's the challenge

140
00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:07.290
that there are

141
00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:11.150
fewer people of working age to pay for the infrastructure.

142
00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:15.170
Growth

143
00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:18.510
has funded development in a lot of those smaller places, and that's not necessarily

144
00:08:18.530 --> 00:08:21.410
going to be the case anymore because a lot of those places are getting both older

145
00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:25.070
and smaller at the same time. So that's going to be the real challenge for the

146
00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:27.370
infrastructure for the smaller places.

147
00:08:29.570 --> 00:08:33.290
Yeah, next slide, please. We'll start on the different areas of infrastructure.

148
00:08:34.331 --> 00:08:35.130
So housing

149
00:08:36.050 --> 00:08:39.951
is obviously a secure and healthy home is the biggest determinant of a healthy old

150
00:08:40.091 --> 00:08:42.740
age, so we really need to get housing right first and foremost.

151
00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:45.650
We already have a really significant housing shortage.

152
00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:49.619
We need nearly half a million homes extra by 2043, according

153
00:08:49.670 --> 00:08:53.290
to Stats New Zealand, and we're falling short by about 5,000 or 10,000 homes a year

154
00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:53.810
at the moment.

155
00:08:55.270 --> 00:08:59.130
In terms of an aging population, what I was most worried about was the shortage of

156
00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:01.090
smaller homes,

157
00:09:02.330 --> 00:09:03.590
accessible houses as well,

158
00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:06.910
both public-owned and on the private market.

159
00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:11.730
We don't have enough existing accessible housing to accommodate

160
00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:14.970
older people with disabilities, let alone to cover future demand.

161
00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:18.690
So in terms of disabilities, I think something like between 17 and

162
00:09:18.730 --> 00:09:22.310
19% of the population counts as disabled in the general

163
00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:25.410
population. But once you get over 65, it's more like 60%.

164
00:09:25.950 --> 00:09:28.790
Of course, not all of those people have mobility problems, but a lot of them do.

165
00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:31.970
So essentially, as the population gets older, we're going to need more and more

166
00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:35.110
accessible housing, and we are already really struggling with demand.

167
00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.630
Housing poverty is also another challenge.

168
00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:43.179
From the statistic here, significantly more people will be renting in the future,

169
00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:47.310
and renting housing, of course, is generally lower quality than

170
00:09:47.690 --> 00:09:51.230
privately owned homes, and that has an impact on public health and overall health

171
00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:54.210
overall, and then ends up putting more pressure on

172
00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:58.750
at the health infrastructure end. So it is a system.

173
00:09:59.130 --> 00:10:01.490
The housing affects public health, which affects how much

174
00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:06.270
health infrastructure we need. So really starting to think of that as a system

175
00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:10.179
and work out how we can improve things at this end to influence our

176
00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:13.950
infrastructure demands over time is going to be really essential.

177
00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:18.710
Yeah, so the report calls for more public housing to be built, especially for older

178
00:10:18.750 --> 00:10:22.430
people, the smaller disability-friendly housing,

179
00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:23.530
especially.

180
00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:27.550
And we should also be thinking, and I think this is just as important, if not more

181
00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:31.100
important, about incentives for private landlords to make their housing more

182
00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:33.410
accessible and to build more smaller housing as well.

183
00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:37.450
I think the market will eventually respond but is responding too

184
00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:38.090
slowly and

185
00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:42.170
probably needs a little push along to make sure that that happens in time.

186
00:10:44.210 --> 00:10:44.790
Yeah.

187
00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:50.930
Also, councils need to be proactively using planning and zoning rules to encourage

188
00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:53.450
a variety of functional and affordable housing as well.

189
00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:56.670
So that's another part of the picture, is what local councils are doing in that

190
00:10:56.730 --> 00:11:00.430
space. Next, we're going to move on to aged care facilities.

191
00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:02.850
I'm trying to rattle through this so we have time for questions.

192
00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:06.450
Yeah, big pinch point here as well.

193
00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:10.490
So there are currently really big gaps in aged care with people falling through

194
00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:13.550
the cracks. Obviously, you would have heard about that in this group.

195
00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:18.490
They either end up in care earlier than they would have liked or miss out on care

196
00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:21.890
entirely. There's going to be around a 12,000 bed shortage by

197
00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:25.890
2032, according to one estimate, and

198
00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.430
that's obviously going to get worse over time with the bulging

199
00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.210
population change. So some areas,

200
00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:36.570
particularly rural areas and some of the smaller regions, are really badly served

201
00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:40.290
compared to the bigger cities, especially with the private, the big six

202
00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:44.340
companies. It's obviously much easier for them to set up in the big areas because

203
00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:46.250
it's easier for them to get suppliers and caterers.

204
00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:47.790
They have a much bigger profit margin there.

205
00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:48.400
So there's not

206
00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:53.650
as much motivation for them to move to some of the smaller rural

207
00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:57.310
areas. You might be waiting for a bed nearly three times as long on the West Coast

208
00:11:57.350 --> 00:11:58.819
as in the Manawatu, for example.

209
00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.290
So we need to increase capacity and beds.

210
00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:06.610
A big part of the problem is the funding models around aged care facilities, and I

211
00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:09.770
know there's a ministerial advisory group looking at that at the moment, which is

212
00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:13.770
fantastic. So we just need to make sure that any recommendations from

213
00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:17.550
that group are backed up with sufficient money to actually increase capacity

214
00:12:17.930 --> 00:12:19.790
dramatically, especially in those smaller areas.

215
00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:23.954
AndAustralia's made really big changes in the space, which we could

216
00:12:23.974 --> 00:12:27.234
really learn from in terms of funding.

217
00:12:27.274 --> 00:12:30.994
And they've got a new capital assistance fund, for example, that helps build

218
00:12:31.174 --> 00:12:33.654
facilities in rural areas and more remote areas.

219
00:12:33.694 --> 00:12:37.114
So I think we need to be really thinking about proactively doing that rather than

220
00:12:37.174 --> 00:12:41.164
just waiting for the market to sort that out, because I don't think the incentives

221
00:12:41.174 --> 00:12:44.614
are quite right for them at the moment to do that adequately.

222
00:12:48.094 --> 00:12:51.714
Yeah. And the other big piece of this picture is investing more and better in

223
00:12:51.754 --> 00:12:53.793
services such as home and community support.

224
00:12:54.314 --> 00:12:57.754
If we can help people more with basic things like personal care, essential

225
00:12:58.994 --> 00:13:02.934
home maintenance, things like even changing light bulbs, helping people to mow

226
00:13:02.974 --> 00:13:06.454
the lawns, that can keep them at home for much longer, and that then takes pressure

227
00:13:06.474 --> 00:13:07.694
off the aged care facilities.

228
00:13:09.274 --> 00:13:11.074
And it's a heck of a lot cheaper as well.

229
00:13:11.094 --> 00:13:12.454
If we look at the next slide,

230
00:13:14.054 --> 00:13:16.854
just these were some figures I pulled out of various government reports.

231
00:13:16.934 --> 00:13:20.014
But in-home care support can cost as little as $20 a day.

232
00:13:20.174 --> 00:13:23.014
Obviously, if you're doing it as well as you can, you could spend a lot more than

233
00:13:23.074 --> 00:13:26.793
that. But if you compare that to aged care facilities, 180, and

234
00:13:26.834 --> 00:13:30.734
hospital care, 1,000 a day, you really want to be investing as much as you can

235
00:13:30.784 --> 00:13:33.674
at that really cheap end because it's just simple economic sense.

236
00:13:37.054 --> 00:13:40.614
Just thinking of it as a systems challenge, obviously every agency has its own

237
00:13:41.274 --> 00:13:43.014
budget line, which makes it harder.

238
00:13:44.214 --> 00:13:47.514
Wings may not want to spend a whole lot extra on helping people with changing light

239
00:13:47.534 --> 00:13:51.294
bulbs or so on. But if we know it's helping the health system to

240
00:13:51.374 --> 00:13:54.554
reduce the demand in terms of building new hospitals or whatever, it's really worth

241
00:13:54.574 --> 00:13:57.434
thinking about how we can sort of break down those silos a wee bit.

242
00:14:02.714 --> 00:14:03.354
So

243
00:14:04.714 --> 00:14:08.264
yeah, I think given the Treasury's concerns in their most

